You have two choices to do this. The first choice is to use `map` operator:

    let fooArray = [ { id: 2,
            name: &#39;woda&#39;,
            price: 45.98,
            quantity: 1,
            createdAt: &#39;2019-07-23T17:50:43.033Z&#39;,
            updatedAt: &#39;2019-07-23T17:50:43.033Z&#39;,
            shopId: 2 },
          { id: 3,
            name: &#39;sham&#39;,
            price: 69.98,
            quantity: 1,
            createdAt: &#39;2019-07-23T17:50:43.033Z&#39;,
            updatedAt: &#39;2019-07-23T17:50:43.033Z&#39;,
            shopId: 2 } ];
    let newArray = [3,4];

Using [destructuring assignment][1] and [...rest][2] operator (this way can be useful when you want to take a nested object):

    fooArray = fooArray.map(({
        quantity,
        ...rest
    }, i) =&gt; ({ ...rest, quantity : quantity * newArray[i]}));
    console.log(fooArray);

or more simpler and readable `map()` function  without `...rest` operator and destructing assignment:

    fooArray = fooArray.map((f,i) =&gt; {
        f.quantity = f.quantity * newArray[i]
        return f;
    });
    console.log(fooArray);

and the second way is to use `foreach` method. As Cerbrus adviced because it is semantically better, shorter code, easier to understand when you want to edit just one value:

    fooArray.forEach((e, i) =&gt; {
        e.quantity = e.quantity * newArray[i];
    })
    console.log(fooArray);

What to use is up to you. We&#39;ve just shows the ways that you can achieve that you want.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Destructuring_assignment
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/rest_parameters

